parameters.name: updates

parameters.name: BCCompletionState
parameters.description:
The business case completion state. The possible values are 
 Summary, Project Info, Goals (DEL), Risks, Cost, Alignment, Custom Data (DE)

parameters.name: ID
parameters.description: ID refers to a Workfront Object ID. You can use a unique Project ID to access a particular project, or you can locate a Project that is associated with a different object, like a Task, by entering that object's unique ID into a project query.

parameters.name: URL
parameters.description: This refers to the Uniform Resource Location of an object or endpoint. You can access a particular project by using its unique URL, locate a project associated with a different object by including its URL in a Project Query, or make changes to objects associated with a project by including their URLs in certain types of requests.

parameters.name: actualBenefit
parameters.description: The actual financial benefit that was gained upon completion of an object, such as a project, or group of objects, such as Tasks.

parameters.name: actualCompletionDate
parameters.description: The Actual Completion Date represents the real date and time a duration-measured object, such as a Task or Project, are marked as completed.

parameters.name: actualCost
parameters.description:
Represents the Actual Costs that were accumulated prior to the completion of a duration-measured object, like a Task or Project.
The Actual Cost of a Project is calculated by: Actual Labor Cost of all Tasks + Actual Expense Cost of all Tasks + Actual Labor Cost of the Project + Actual Expense Cost of the Project.

parameters.name: actualDurationMinutes
parameters.description: The difference, in minutes, between the Actual Start Date and the Actual Completion Date of a duration-measured object. In other words, this is how long a Task, Project, or other duration-measured object actually took to complete, in minutes.

parameters.name: actualExpenseCost
parameters.description: Actual Expense Cost is the final cost of expenses that has accumulated at the completion of an object, like a project, or a group of objects, such as Tasks. The Actual Expense Cost of a project is the final total of expense costs accumulated by the completion of a Project.

parameters.name: actualLaborCost
parameters.description: Actual Labor Cost is the final labor cost that has accumulated at the completion of an object, like a project, or a group of objects, such as Tasks. The Actual Labor Cost of a Project is the final total of Labor Costs that accumulated by the completion of a project.

parameters.name: actualRevenue
parameters.description:
Actual Revenue is the revenue associated with the Actual Hours of Tasks. That is, the revenue associated with the Actual Hours of the tasks becomes the Actual Revenue.
For example, if a task with User Hourly Revenue Type is planned to take 2 hours and the user assigned to it has an hourly rate of $30 an hour, then the Planned Revenue of the task is $60. When the task is completed, if the user logs just 1.5 hours as the actual time spent to finish the task, the Actual Revenue amount is $45

parameters.name: actualRiskCost
parameters.description: Actual Risk Cost is the Actual Cost value that was assigned to a Risk object. The Actual Risk Cost of a Project is a summation of the Actual Costs associated with all the Risk objects that were specified on a project.

parameters.name: actualStartDate
parameters.description: Actual Start Date is the actual date that work begins on a Project, Task, or Issue object. That is, the Actual Start Date of a project, task, or issue is not populated when these items are created. The Actual Start Date is populated when work actually starts on a project, task, or issue.

parameters.name: actualValue
parameters.description: Actual Value

parameters.name: actualWorkRequired
parameters.description:
Work Required is the duration of Task hours multiplied by the number of resources assigned to that task. Actual work required is a summation of these values at the completion of a project. The formula looks something like:
Actual Work Required = SUM(Duration of the task in hours) x (Percent allocated towards tasks for each resource).

parameters.name: alignment
parameters.description: Alignment is a reference to the Alignment Score that is generated after a Score Card is completed for a project. A Project Alignment Score = The sum of the question points from the scorecard met at a given time/ The sum of the possible points on the scorecard. The Portfolio Alignment Score = The sum of the percentages of the project alignment scores/ Number of projects in the portfolio. If a project does not have a scorecard associated with it, and therefore it does not have an alignment score, it is considered to have a 0% alignment in the portfolio. The project is taken into account in the number of projects in the portfolio.

parameters.name: alignmentScoreCardID
parameters.description: Alignment Scorecard ID refers to the unique ID that is assigned to a Score Card. An Alignment Scorecard ID is directly related to the project for which the Scorecard was created.

parameters.name: approvalCompletionDate
parameters.description: The date and time that an approval path for a specific project was marked Complete.

parameters.name: approvalProcessID
parameters.description: The unique ID of an Approval Process that has been created in Workfront.

parameters.name: approvalStartDate
parameters.description: The date and time that an approval path starts. This is when the project, task, or issue is set to the status that was selected in the Start Approval Process When the Status is Set To field when the Approval Process was created.

parameters.name: auditTypes
parameters.description:
Audits are system messages that record actions occurring in a Workfront environment. The following audit types are recorded: 
 Scope Change, Attachment Action, General Edit, Status Change, Note, Combined Entry, Error Entry, Status Change, Subscription Change

parameters.name: The baseline is a project snapshot that represents key pieces of data included in the initial project plan as approved prior to execution. A baseline is used to compare those data points from the current plan to the original plan to identify problem tasks, scope creep, and other trends over time. Auto Baseline Recur On can be set so a baseline is automatically created on projects.
parameters.description: Auto Baseline Recur On

parameters.name: autoBaselineRecurrenceType
parameters.description:
Auto Baseline Recurrence Type. Possible values are: 
 Daily, Weekly, Bi-Weekly, Semi-Monthly, Monthly, Custom

parameters.name: billedRevenue
parameters.description: Revenue billed to clients or other parties, which is captured in billing records.

parameters.name: budget
parameters.description: The Budget set for the project. This is manually specified by the project owner.

parameters.name: budgetStatus
parameters.description:
Indicates whether the project is currently added to the capacity planner, and if the budget calculation has been completed for it. Possible values are: 
 Not Included (0), Included but not Calculated (1),  Included and Calculated (2).

parameters.name: budgetedCompletionDate
parameters.description: This is a deprecated field that shows the date when the budgeting of resources ends, as defined in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of the Business Case of a project, or the Capacity Planner.

parameters.name: budgetedCost
parameters.description:
The Budgeted Cost for the project is calculated using the following formula:
Budgeted Cost = Budgeted Expense Cost + Budgeted Labor Cost + Fixed Cost of the project

parameters.name: budgetedHours
parameters.description: These are the hours that are budgeted for your resources to complete work on a Project. This field refers to both hours budgeted in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of a project (or in the Capacity Planner), and hours budgeted in the Resource Budgeting area of the Business Case (or in the Resource Planner).

parameters.name: budgetedLaborCost
parameters.description:
This is the cost associated with the hours that are budgeted for your resources to complete work on Projects. The Budgeted Labor Cost in a project report is calculated using the following formula:
Budgeted Labor Cost = SUM(Job Role Cost per Hour * Budgeted Hours per Job Role)
This field refers to both labor costs for hours budgeted in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of a project (or in the Capacity Planner), and hours budgeted in the Resource Budgeting area of the Business Case (or in the Resource Planner).

parameters.name: budgetedStartDate
parameters.description: This is a deprecated field that shows the date when the budgeting of resources starts, as defined in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of the Business Case of a project, or the Capacity Planner. The field is available in project and task reports.

parameters.name: categoryID
parameters.description: A category is a custom form. You can build reports for this object and you can show it in other object reports, as well. A category ID is a unique ID that is assigned to a category at its creation. Not all objects can have a custom form, or category. The following objects can have a custom form: Project, Task, Issue, Portfolio, Document, Expense, Program, User, Company

parameters.name: companyID
parameters.description: This is an internal object.

parameters.name: completionType
parameters.description:
Completion Type indicates how a project is marked as Complete. If Manual is selected, users must manually select the Complete status for the project. If Automatic is selected, the project is marked complete when all the tasks and issues are completed. The possible values for Completion Type are: 
 Automatic, Manual

parameters.name: condition
parameters.description:
This is a visual representation of the progress of a task, issue or project. For projects, the condition can be manually set or it can be automatically set by Workfront, based on the progress status of the project. The possible values for the project condition are: 
 On Target, At Risk, In Trouble

parameters.name: conditionType
parameters.description:
Condition type determines whether the condition of a project is set manually, or if it is based on the progress status of the tasks in the project. The possible values for the condition type are: 
 Manual, Progress Status

parameters.name: convertedOpTaskEntryDate
parameters.description: The Entry Date of the original issue that was converted into a project or task.

parameters.name: convertedOpTaskName
parameters.description: The name of the original issue that was converted into a project or task.

parameters.name: convertedOpTaskOriginatorID
parameters.description: The unique Workfront ID of the user who originated an issue that was later converted into a project or task.

parameters.name: cpi
parameters.description: The Cost Performance Index (CPI) describes the relationship (at the project or task level) between the planned cost and actual cost. Project Managers review this metric to identify tasks or projects currently tracking under or over cost at a given point. Cost can be measured in hours or dollars, depending on your Performance Index Method (PIM). For additional information about CPI, including how it is calculated under different circumstances, please visit the Workfront Experience CPI help article.

parameters.name: csi
parameters.description: The Cost Schedule Performance Index (CSI) is an automatic calculation which combines the Cost Performance Index (CPI) and Schedule Performance Index (SPI) into one general metric that balances cost and schedule. By multiplying these values together, a single metric can account for a protracted schedule at a lower budget or vice versa. Project managers may use this to determine general project or task health when cost is sacrificed to drive schedule mid-project. For additional information about CSI, please visit the Workfront Experience CSI help article.

parameters.name: currency
parameters.description: Project Managers and other users can configure a project to use a currency other than the default currency. This allows you to display financial information on your project in the desired currency when calculating labor costs and revenue. For additional information about currency, please visit the Workfront Experience Default Currency help article.

parameters.name: currentApprovalStepID
parameters.description: Approval processes have unique Workfront IDs, but the stages in them have their own Workfront IDs. Current Approval Stage ID is the ID of the Approval Stage that the project is currently in.

parameters.name: customerID
parameters.description: This is an internal object.

parameters.name: displayOrder

parameters.name: durationMinutes
parameters.description: Duration in Minutes

parameters.name: eac
parameters.description: As a performance metric, the Estimate at Completion (EAC) represents the projected total cost of your project or task when it completes. As a setting, it allows you to define how the EAC value should be calculated. For additional information about EAC, please visit the Workfront Experience Estimate At Completion help article.

parameters.name: eacCalculationMethod
parameters.description:
As a performance metric, the Estimate at Completion (EAC) represents the projected total cost of your project or task when it completes. In Workfront, the calculation for EAC depends on the selected Performance Index Method (PIM) of the project. The possible values are: 
 Calculate at Project Level (P), Roll up from Tasks/Subtasks (T)

parameters.name: enableAutoBaselines
parameters.description: The baseline is a project snapshot that represents key pieces of data included in the initial project plan as approved prior to execution. A baseline is used to compare those data points from the current plan to the original plan to identify problem tasks, scope creep, and other trends over time. When Enable Auto Baselines is enabled, Workfront automatically creates a baseline (snapshot) of task and project details when the status of the project changes to Current.

parameters.name: entryDate

parameters.name: estCompletionDate
parameters.description: The Estimated Completion Date is calculated based on the current progress of the work on the task. For example, if today is September 23 and the task has not started yet, the Estimated Completion Date is September 27 (it should be completed after 4 days, assuming that the work starts immediately). If the task is 25% completed today, the Estimated Completion Date is September 25 (it should be completed after 2 days, which is the remaining 75% of the Duration of the task).

parameters.name: estStartDate
parameters.description: Estimated Start Date is a summary of different start-time constraints associated with an object. For example, setting the Task Constraint to Must Start On manually sets the Planned Start Date to a specific date. The Projected Start Date in this case matches the Planned Start Date. In the case of this constraint, Workfront analyzes the task to calculate when it will start based on its predecessor relationships. This calculation is stored as the Estimated Start Date.

parameters.name: performanceIndexMethod
parameters.description:
The Performance Index Method (PIM) for the project controls the method Workfront uses to calculate project performance metrics such as Cost Performance Index (CPI), Cost Schedule Performance Index (CSI), Schedule Performance Index (SPI), and Estimate At Completion (EAC). When the Performance Index Method is Hour-Based, Workfront uses the Planned Hours in calculating the CPI and EAC of the project, and the EAC of the project displays as a number, in hours. When the Performance Index Method is Cost-Based, Workfront uses the Planned Labor Cost in calculating the CPI and EAC of the project, and the EAC displays as a currency value. Possible values for Performance Index Method are: 
 Hour-Based, Cost-Based

parameters.name: personal
parameters.description: This is a boolean parameter that will return a true value if a task is a personal task, and false if it is not.

parameters.name: plannedBenefit
parameters.description: The Planned Benefit is the estimated dollar amount that an organization might benefit from if a project is completed.

parameters.name: plannedCompletionDate
parameters.description: The Planned Completion Date of a project can be set manually or automatically, depending on whether you schedule the project from the Start or from the Completion Date. The Planned Completion Date of a project is automatically calculated by Workfront when you schedule the project from Start Date. As you start adding tasks to your project, the Planned Completion Date of the project calculates based on the total Duration of all of the tasks.

parameters.name: plannedCost
parameters.description: The Planned Cost of a project is calculated by the following formula: Planned Project Cost = Planned Labor Cost of all tasks + Planned Expense cost of all tasks + Planned Expense Cost of the project.

parameters.name: plannedExpenseCost
parameters.description: Planned Expense Cost is the total of the Planned Amounts of all the expenses on the project.

parameters.name: plannedLaborCost
parameters.description: Planned Labor Cost is the total of all Planned Labor Costs for all tasks. The rate can be calculated by the rate or the user, depending on the Cost Type that is set on a given task. For additional information see the Workfront help article on Tracking Costs.

parameters.name: plannedRevenue
parameters.description:
Workfront can track revenue automatically when tasks and projects are created based on the Planned Hours or the Actual Hours of the tasks. The revenue associated with the Planned Hours of the tasks becomes the Planned Revenue. Workfront calculates Planned Revene according to the following formulas: 
 Planned revenue for a project = SUM(Planned revenue for all tasks in the project). 
 Planned revenue for a task = (Planned hours X Billing per hour rate) + Fixed Revenue for the task.

parameters.name: plannedRiskCost
parameters.description:
The Planned Risk Cost of a project takes into account the Potential Costs of the project and their probability of occurring. 
 Workfront calculates the Potential Risk Cost of a project using the following formula: 
 Potential Risk Cost =SUM(Potential Risk Costs * Risk Probability)

parameters.name: plannedStartDate
parameters.description: The Planned Start Date of a project can be set manually or automatically, depending on whether you schedule the project from the Start or from the Completion Date. You must manually set the Planned Start Date of a project when you schedule the project from Start Date. The Planned Start Date of a project is automatically calculated by Workfront when you schedule the project from Completion Date. As you start adding tasks to your project, the Planned Start Date of the project calculates based on the total Duration of all of the tasks, counting backwards from the Planned Completion Date.

parameters.name: plannedValue
parameters.description:
Planned value is the total expected value of a project after calculating its benefit and removing its costs. Planned Value is a field from the legacy resource planner. It has been replaced in newer tools with Project Net Value, although the formula is slightly different. 
 The formula for Planned Value is: 
 Planned Value = Planned Benefit - Planned Risk Cost - Budgeted Cost.

parameters.name: progressStatus

Workfront determines the Progress Status of a task by looking at the progression of the task across its timeline. Possible values are: 
 On Time, At Risk, Behind, Late

parameters.name: projectedCompletionDate
parameters.description: Projected Completion Date is a real-time, calculated indicator of when the project, task, or issue will be completed. When the project, task, or issue is marked as Completed, the Projected Completion Date changes to the date of the Actual Completion Date.

parameters.description:
Resource Planner Budgeted Labor Cost of a project is calculated by the following formula:
Budgeted Labor Cost = SUM(Budgeted Hours for each job role on the project * Cost per Hour rate of each job role on the project). Where the Budgeted Hours are the hours budgeted for job roles in the Resource Budgeting area of the project or the Resource Planner.

parameters.name: resourcePoolID
parameters.description: A Resource Pool is a collection of users that are needed at the same time for the completion of a project. The Legacy Resource Pool ID is the unique identifier that is assigned to a resource pool by Workfront.

parameters.name: risk

 None (0), Very Low (1), Low (2), Medium (3), High (4), Very High (5)

parameters.name: scheduleMode
parameters.description:
Schedule Mode determines whether a project is scheduled from the Start Date or the Completion Date. If Scheduled from Start Date, the first task of the project has the same Planned Start Date as the project, and the Completion Date is calculated based on the Duration of all tasks in the project. If Scheduled from Completion Date, the last task of the project has the same Completion Date as the project, and Start Date is calculated based on subtracting the Duration of all tasks in the project from the Completion Date. Possible values for Schedule Mode are: 
 Start Date, Completion Date

parameters.name: selectedOnPortfolioOptimizer
parameters.description: Selected on Portfolio Optimizer is a status which indicates whether or not a project has been selected as part of a group using the Portfolio Optimizer.

parameters.name: spi
parameters.description:
The Schedule Performance Index (SPI) describes the relationship between the planned schedule and actual schedule. Workfront calculates SPI at the project and task levels. Project managers review this metric to identify whether tasks or projects are currently tracking ahead of or behind schedule. Project managers understand that a SPI value of 1 means the project is on plan or on schedule.  Values greater than 1 indicate a project is ahead of schedule, and values less than 1 mean a project is behind schedule.  The further from 1, the greater deviation from the plan.
Workfront calculates SPI by the following formula:
 SPI = (Total Planned Hours x % Complete) / Planned Hours Scheduled to Date*
 *If Planned Hours Scheduled to Date = 0, SPI = 1.

parameters.name: sponsorID

parameters.name: status
parameters.description:
You can use the status of a project to show users in the system in what stage of development a project is found at a given time. A project can be either active or not active in Workfront, depending on what stage of development it is in. For example, when an approval is pending on the business case of a project, or when a project is considered completed or dead, the project is not considered active. If a project is currently being worked on, or has been requested, or is in the planning phase, it is considered active. Possible values for Status are: 
 Current, Dead, On Hold, Planning, Complete, Requested, Approved, Rejected, Idea

Summary Completion Type indicates how parent tasks are marked as Complete. If Manual is selected, users must manually update the percent complete and the status of the parent tasks, independently of what changes are made to the children tasks. If Automatic is selected, the parent tasks are marked as Complete and they update their percent complete automatically, as the children tasks are completed and the percent complete of the children is updated. Possible values for Summary Completion Type are: 
 Automatic, Manual

When the project timeline is updated, it is recalculated based on changes made to the project, its tasks, or changes made to another project that the timeline is dependent on. The possible values for Update TYpe are: 
 Automatic Only (ATYO), Change Only (EVNT), Automatic and On Change (AUTO), Manual (MANU)

parameters.name: actualBenefit
parameters.description: The actual financial benefit that was gained upon completion of an object, such as a project, or group of objects, such as Tasks.

parameters.name: actualCompletionDate
parameters.description: The Actual Completion Date represents the real date and time a duration-measured object, such as a Task or Project, are marked as completed.

parameters.name: actualCost
parameters.description:
Represents the Actual Costs that were accumulated prior to the completion of a duration-measured object, like a Task or Project.
The Actual Cost of a Project is calculated by: Actual Labor Cost of all Tasks + Actual Expense Cost of all Tasks + Actual Labor Cost of the Project + Actual Expense Cost of the Project.

parameters.name: actualDurationMinutes
parameters.description: The difference, in minutes, between the Actual Start Date and the Actual Completion Date of a duration-measured object. In other words, this is how long a Task, Project, or other duration-measured object actually took to complete, in minutes.

parameters.name: actualExpenseCost
parameters.description: Actual Expense Cost is the final cost of expenses that has accumulated at the completion of an object, like a project, or a group of objects, such as Tasks. The Actual Expense Cost of a project is the final total of expense costs accumulated by the completion of a Project.

parameters.name: actualLaborCost
parameters.description: Actual Labor Cost is the final labor cost that has accumulated at the completion of an object, like a project, or a group of objects, such as Tasks. The Actual Labor Cost of a Project is the final total of Labor Costs that accumulated by the completion of a project.

parameters.name: actualRevenue
parameters.description:
Actual Revenue is the revenue associated with the Actual Hours of Tasks. That is, the revenue associated with the Actual Hours of the tasks becomes the Actual Revenue.
For example, if a task with User Hourly Revenue Type is planned to take 2 hours and the user assigned to it has an hourly rate of $30 an hour, then the Planned Revenue of the task is $60. When the task is completed, if the user logs just 1.5 hours as the actual time spent to finish the task, the Actual Revenue amount is $45

parameters.name: actualRiskCost
parameters.description: Actual Risk Cost is the Actual Cost value that was assigned to a Risk object. The Actual Risk Cost of a Project is a summation of the Actual Costs associated with all the Risk objects that were specified on a project.

parameters.name: actualStartDate
parameters.description: Actual Start Date is the actual date that work begins on a Project, Task, or Issue object. That is, the Actual Start Date of a project, task, or issue is not populated when these items are created. The Actual Start Date is populated when work actually starts on a project, task, or issue.

parameters.name: actualValue
parameters.description: Actual Value

parameters.name: actualWorkRequired
parameters.description:
Work Required is the duration of Task hours multiplied by the number of resources assigned to that task. Actual work required is a summation of these values at the completion of a project. The formula looks something like:
Actual Work Required = SUM(Duration of the task in hours) x (Percent allocated towards tasks for each resource).

parameters.name: alignment
parameters.description: Alignment is a reference to the Alignment Score that is generated after a Score Card is completed for a project. A Project Alignment Score = The sum of the question points from the scorecard met at a given time/ The sum of the possible points on the scorecard. The Portfolio Alignment Score = The sum of the percentages of the project alignment scores/ Number of projects in the portfolio. If a project does not have a scorecard associated with it, and therefore it does not have an alignment score, it is considered to have a 0% alignment in the portfolio. The project is taken into account in the number of projects in the portfolio.

Audits are system messages that record actions occurring in a Workfront environment. The following audit types are recorded:

parameters.name: budgetedCompletionDate
parameters.description: This is a deprecated field that shows the date when the budgeting of resources ends, as defined in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of the Business Case of a project, or the Capacity Planner.

parameters.name: budgetedCost

Budgeted Cost = Budgeted Expense Cost + Budgeted Labor Cost + Fixed Cost of the project

This field refers to both hours budgeted in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of a project (or in the Capacity Planner), and hours budgeted in the Resource Budgeting area of the Business Case (or in the Resource Planner).

parameters.name: budgetedLaborCost
parameters.description:
This is the cost associated with the hours that are budgeted for your resources to complete work on Projects. The Budgeted Labor Cost in a project report is calculated using the following formula:
Budgeted Labor Cost = SUM(Job Role Cost per Hour * Budgeted Hours per Job Role)
This field refers to both labor costs for hours budgeted in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of a project (or in the Capacity Planner), and hours budgeted in the Resource Budgeting area of the Business Case (or in the Resource Planner).

A category ID is a unique ID that is assigned to a category at its creation. Not all objects can have a custom form, or category. The following objects can have a custom form: Project, Task, Issue, Portfolio, Document, Expense, Program, User, Company.

By multiplying these values together, a single metric can account for a protracted schedule at a lower budget or vice versa. Project managers may use this to determine general project or task health when cost is sacrificed to drive schedule mid-project. For additional information about CSI, please visit the Workfront Experience CSI help article.

parameters.name: performanceIndexMethod
parameters.description:
The Performance Index Method (PIM) for the project controls the method Workfront uses to calculate project performance metrics such as Cost Performance Index (CPI), Cost Schedule Performance Index (CSI), Schedule Performance Index (SPI), and Estimate At Completion (EAC). When the Performance Index Method is Hour-Based, Workfront uses the Planned Hours in calculating the CPI and EAC of the project, and the EAC of the project displays as a number, in hours. When the Performance Index Method is Cost-Based, Workfront uses the Planned Labor Cost in calculating the CPI and EAC of the project, and the EAC displays as a currency value. Possible values for Performance Index Method are: 
 Hour-Based, Cost-Based

parameters.name: personal
parameters.description: This is a boolean parameter that will return a true value if a task is a personal task, and false if it is not.

parameters.name: plannedBenefit
parameters.description: The Planned Benefit is the estimated dollar amount that an organization might benefit from if a project is completed.

parameters.name: plannedCompletionDate
parameters.description: The Planned Completion Date of a project can be set manually or automatically, depending on whether you schedule the project from the Start or from the Completion Date. The Planned Completion Date of a project is automatically calculated by Workfront when you schedule the project from Start Date. As you start adding tasks to your project, the Planned Completion Date of the project calculates based on the total Duration of all of the tasks.

parameters.name: plannedCost
parameters.description: The Planned Cost of a project is calculated by the following formula: Planned Project Cost = Planned Labor Cost of all tasks + Planned Expense cost of all tasks + Planned Expense Cost of the project.

parameters.name: plannedExpenseCost
parameters.description: Planned Expense Cost is the total of the Planned Amounts of all the expenses on the project.

parameters.name: plannedLaborCost
parameters.description: Planned Labor Cost is the total of all Planned Labor Costs for all tasks. The rate can be calculated by the rate or the user, depending on the Cost Type that is set on a given task. For additional information see the Workfront help article on Tracking Costs.

parameters.name: plannedRevenue
parameters.description:
Workfront can track revenue automatically when tasks and projects are created based on the Planned Hours or the Actual Hours of the tasks. The revenue associated with the Planned Hours of the tasks becomes the Planned Revenue. Workfront calculates Planned Revene according to the following formulas: 
 Planned revenue for a project = SUM(Planned revenue for all tasks in the project). 
 Planned revenue for a task = (Planned hours X Billing per hour rate) + Fixed Revenue for the task.

parameters.name: plannedRiskCost
parameters.description:
The Planned Risk Cost of a project takes into account the Potential Costs of the project and their probability of occurring. 
 Workfront calculates the Potential Risk Cost of a project using the following formula: 
 Potential Risk Cost =SUM(Potential Risk Costs * Risk Probability)

parameters.name: plannedStartDate
parameters.description: The Planned Start Date of a project can be set manually or automatically, depending on whether you schedule the project from the Start or from the Completion Date. You must manually set the Planned Start Date of a project when you schedule the project from Start Date. The Planned Start Date of a project is automatically calculated by Workfront when you schedule the project from Completion Date. As you start adding tasks to your project, the Planned Start Date of the project calculates based on the total Duration of all of the tasks, counting backwards from the Planned Completion Date.

parameters.name: plannedValue
parameters.description:
Planned value is the total expected value of a project after calculating its benefit and removing its costs. Planned Value is a field from the legacy resource planner. It has been replaced in newer tools with Project Net Value, although the formula is slightly different. 
 The formula for Planned Value is: 
 Planned Value = Planned Benefit - Planned Risk Cost - Budgeted Cost.

parameters.name: resourcePlannerBudgetedLaborCost
parameters.description:
Resource Planner Budgeted Labor Cost of a project is calculated by the following formula:
Budgeted Labor Cost = SUM(Budgeted Hours for each job role on the project * Cost per Hour rate of each job role on the project). Where the Budgeted Hours are the hours budgeted for job roles in the Resource Budgeting area of the project or the Resource Planner.

parameters.name: resourcePoolID

parameters.name: risk
parameters.description:
Risks are possible events that prevent your project from finishing on time or within budget.
 You can add risks to your projects in the planning phase to identify potential obstacles prior to the approval of any work. The possible values for Risk are: 
 None (0), Very Low (1), Low (2), Medium (3), High (4), Very High (5)

parameters.name: scheduleMode
parameters.description:
Schedule Mode determines whether a project is scheduled from the Start Date or the Completion Date. If Scheduled from Start Date, the first task of the project has the same Planned Start Date as the project, and the Completion Date is calculated based on the Duration of all tasks in the project. If Scheduled from Completion Date, the last task of the project has the same Completion Date as the project, and Start Date is calculated based on subtracting the Duration of all tasks in the project from the Completion Date. Possible values for Schedule Mode are: 
 Start Date, Completion Date

parameters.name: spi
parameters.description:
The Schedule Performance Index (SPI) describes the relationship between the planned schedule and actual schedule. Workfront calculates SPI at the project and task levels. Project managers review this metric to identify whether tasks or projects are currently tracking ahead of or behind schedule. Project managers understand that a SPI value of 1 means the project is on plan or on schedule.  Values greater than 1 indicate a project is ahead of schedule, and values less than 1 mean a project is behind schedule.  The further from 1, the greater deviation from the plan.
Workfront calculates SPI by the following formula:
 SPI = (Total Planned Hours x % Complete) / Planned Hours Scheduled to Date*
 *If Planned Hours Scheduled to Date = 0, SPI = 1.

parameters.name: sponsorID

parameters.name: status
parameters.description:
You can use the status of a project to show users in the system in what stage of development a project is found at a given time. A project can be either active or not active in Workfront, depending on what stage of development it is in. For example, when an approval is pending on the business case of a project, or when a project is considered completed or dead, the project is not considered active. If a project is currently being worked on, or has been requested, or is in the planning phase, it is considered active. Possible values for Status are: 
 Current, Dead, On Hold, Planning, Complete, Requested, Approved, Rejected, Idea

parameters.name: summaryCompletionType
parameters.description:
Summary Completion Type indicates how parent tasks are marked as Complete. If Manual is selected, users must manually update the percent complete and the status of the parent tasks, independently of what changes are made to the children tasks. If Automatic is selected, the parent tasks are marked as Complete and they update their percent complete automatically, as the children tasks are completed and the percent complete of the children is updated. Possible values for Summary Completion Type are: 
 Automatic, Manual

 Automatic Only (ATYO), Change Only (EVNT), Automatic and On Change (AUTO), Manual (MANU)
